          <msContents>
            <summary>Small manuscript likely carried as a kind of pocket booklet for use in private meditation and prayer. Dedicated to praising the importance of the well-known Hindu work, the Bhagavadgītā, as a sacred work and expounding on the merits of its recitation, comparing it to visiting various sacred pilgrimage sites (tīrtha). Presented as a dialogue between the wild boar form of Viṣṇu called, Varāha, and the goddess earth, Pṛthivī.</summary>
            <textLang>In Sanskrit</textLang>
            <msItem>
              <title>Gītāmāhātmya</title>
              <respStmt>
                <resp>scribe</resp>
                <persName>Jośī, Govinda</persName>
              </respStmt>
              <respStmt>
                <resp>former owner</resp>
                <persName>Moḍaka, Vināyaka</persName>
              </respStmt>
              <colophon>Colophon: it[i] śrīvarāhapurāṇe śrībhagavatpṛthivīsaṃvāde gītāmahātmyaṃ saṃpūrṇaṃ // śrīkṛṣṇārpaṇam astu // idaṃ jośī upanāmakagoviṃdena likhitaṃ // moḍakopanāmakavināyakena pustakaṃ (f. 3r).</colophon>
            </msItem>
